{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1106"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1106"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.12,0.05,0.19,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1106"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"153"},{"type":"tags","id":"2133"},{"type":"tags","id":"4163"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man is undergoing elective surgery for a carcinoma of the colon. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. During the procedure, a wide-based outpouching is found on the small intestine (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leave it alone","Biopsy section","Invagination and oversew","Local resection","Resection with adjacent section of bowel"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum, a congenital defect, and most are found incidentally at surgery for some other condition. Provided they are wide-based (such as this one) and do not show any evidence of invagination, they can be \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft well alone\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf it had a narrow base and long length, a \u003Cstrong\u003Elocal resection\u003C/strong\u003E may be required as these features would increase the risk of intestinal obstruction including a volvulus, intussusception, or stricture formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeckel\u0027s diverticulum may require intervention if it causes intestinal bleeding, which can occur if there is ectopic gastric or pancreatic tissue present. These tissues can produce acid, leading to mucosal ulceration on the mesenteric side of the intestine, resulting in bleeding. Despite these potential complications, Meckel\u0027s diverticulum does not typically require \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiopsy\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eresection of the adjacent small bowel\u003C/strong\u003E. Additionally, an\u003Cstrong\u003E invagination procedure with oversewing\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for Meckel\u0027s diverticulum. If surgical removal is necessary, it usually involves a local resection of the diverticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey pieces of information about Meckel\u0027s diverticulum can be remembered using the Rule of 2s:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2% of the population affected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMale:female ratio is 2:1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2 feet from ileocaecal valve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2 inches long\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2 types of ectopic tissue also known as \u0027rest\u0027 (ectopic tissue includes: gastric and pancreatic tissue).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meckel diverticulum discovered incidentally during surgery does not require intervention if it is asymptomatic, wide-based, and without evidence of invagination.","Surgical resection is reserved for Meckel diverticulum with a narrow base, long length, or if it is symptomatic (e.g., bleeding, obstruction)."],"references":["Hansen CC, Soreide K. Systematic review of epidemiology, presentation, and management of Meckel\u2019s diverticulum in the 21st century. Medicine (Baltimore). 2018;97:35. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30170459/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1106"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16057"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16057"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/24c51a04-9d30-45d4-9acf-fa248d3148d1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/24c51a04-9d30-45d4-9acf-fa248d3148d1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-09T11:59:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-09T12:02:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1106"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relat